column1: Between 1 July 2017 and 30 June 2018, will an armed group from Myanmar engage in a campaign that systematically kills 1,000 or more civilians in Myanmar?
column6: ['Security and Conflict']
column11: The EWP is asking forecasters to help provide early risk assessments to policy makers, NGOs, and other international actors about the systematic killing of civilians resulting in mass fatalities (Early Warning Project). This question is part of a series of quarterly questions (Good Judgment Inc). It will be suspended on 30 September 2017 and will be resolved in July 2018 after EWP assesses the situation in Myanmar from July 2017 through June 2018. Armed groups include but are not limited to state security forces, rebel armies, and other militias. Campaigns that systematically kill civilians include, but are not limited to, policies which intentionally kill civilians en masse (e.g., military strategies that intentionally target civilians, mass execution of a specific group) and policies that knowingly result in widespread death (e.g., mass starvation, confiscation of health care supplies, forced relocation). In general, unrelated executions of individuals or the accidental killing of civilians in war will not be considered a campaign to systematically kill civilians. If an armed group is engaged in multiple campaigns that systematically kill civilians (e.g., in different geographic areas, or targeted against separate civilian groups) those fatalities will be counted separately and the question will only resolve as yes if 1,000 civilian fatalities occur in one or more campaigns. See Early Warning Project for examples. See GJ’s FAQ on forecasting questions like this. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: Still think issues with counting and classifying will predominate in the resolution of this question, but seems to me that the on-going campaign includes forced relocation.

I dont't expect this to escalate further. It's hard to access the death toll of the clearance operations that have been halted since the beginning of September. It is def. somewhere above 400, but I doubt that it surpasses 1000. As I can't be certain of that, I'll give this 25%.

Raising to 50%, waiting for Aung San Suu Kyi big speech. I spoke with Germans in Myanmar yesterday, the rally around the flag effect is immense and people in Myanmar don't pay too much attention to how this issue is being reported on outside their country. While Aung San Suu Kyi obv. will adress this issue in her speech, she will prob. continue to focus on other conflicts in Myanmar nontheless as also the population doesn't care too much about the fate of the Rohingya. I assume she will frame this issue as one of outside militias vs. the state of Myanmar against which people will have to unify. There are a lot of fake news out there (from both sides) and most people inside Myanmar probably believe that fleeing Rohingyas burned down their houses themselves to be able to accuse the government of ethnic cleansing and damage it's reputation. There are some video campaigns suggesting exactly that (although they are flawed as videos allegedly displaying residents burning down their own houses show the same man in multiply villages etc.). Meaning: There are militias in civilian clothing perpetrating atrocities & as the situation is developing right now, it is highly unlikely that the perpetrators will be held accountable. If clearance operation continue, it can therefore be assumed that the death toll will continue to rise.
Based on general news and GJP consensus.

In my copious free time I wonder whether folks must die within in Myanmar if they wish to be counted, or can they contribute to the total if they flee Myanmar and then die in Bangladesh of wounds or starvation or disease. The deaths of the latter group are surely down to a discrete campaign by the Myamar military--but who knows how the scorers will deal with such matters?

Myanmar army still claims only targeting insurgents, but ... awful lot of people on the move. Lots of houses burnt. Documentation & # of deaths intentionally caused are weak points. More than 1000 dead plausible, but some will be due to conditions.

Iran and Turkey are sending aid to the Rohinga/ jumping from 5 to 70 percent http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2017/09/iran-turkey-myanmar-rohingya-muslims-aid-refugees.html?utm_source=Boomtrain&utm_medium=manual&utm_campaign=20170912&bt_ee=Z8TvtZIvd4gEPzsLiBqVTJ9lWzq9gFd/DZquptMztXJIlKy526pBfsJrc382Cz+N&bt_ts=1505231866933 The two presidents, speaking along the sidelines of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation summit on science and technology in Astana, Kazakhstan, over the weekend, stressed the importance of taking action to put an end to the violence against the Rohingya. Rouhani said in Astana that the plight of the Rohingya, along with other situations in the Muslim world, including Iraq, Syria, Yemen and Palestine, showed the need for unity. Hundreds of thousands of Rohingya crossed through their country's border with Bangladesh after Myanmar’s army attacked their villages in Rakhine state. Myanmar’s army said its posts were attacked first by militants. Some of the Rohingya who fled to Bangladesh reported tales of atrocities by the army against civilians.
